PROJECT 7: CloudFront + ELB + Auto Scaling
Date: Day 10
What I built:

Attempted CloudFront distribution setup with S3 origin and OAC configuration
Created Application Load Balancer (dipesh-alb) inside dipesh-security-vpc
Configured ALB with internet-facing scheme across 2 availability zones
Created Target Group (dipesh-target-group) with EC2 instance registered
Created Auto Scaling Group (dipesh-asg) with launch template
Configured scaling policy targeting 70% CPU utilization
Tested load balancer DNS endpoint
Deleted all resources after testing to avoid charges

Security concepts applied:

Load balancer placed inside custom VPC
Security group applied to load balancer
Auto Scaling ensures high availability
Resources deleted after use — responsible cost management
Correct deletion order followed to prevent orphaned resources

Challenges faced and resolved:

CloudFront blocked by account verification requirement
AWS Support contact required for new accounts
Documented CloudFront configuration knowledge
Will complete after account verification
Load balancer DNS showed site cannot be reached
Diagnosed root cause — no web server installed on EC2
Understood difference between infrastructure and application layer
ELB was working correctly — EC2 had no application to serve
Auto Scaling launched extra EC2 instance during testing
Understood Auto Scaling replaces unhealthy instances automatically
Followed correct deletion order: ASG first then LB then Target Group
Extra instance terminated automatically when ASG was deleted

Real world value:

Application Load Balancer is used by every major company for high availability
Auto Scaling is essential for handling traffic spikes cost effectively
CloudFront CDN reduces latency for global users
Understanding deletion order prevents orphaned resources and unexpected charges
Cost awareness demonstrated by deleting lab resources after testing

Key learnings:

EC2 is just infrastructure — web server software must be installed separately
CloudFront delivers content faster but needs a web server behind it
Auto Scaling Group controls EC2 — always delete ASG before stopping EC2
Load balancer requires subnets in minimum 2 availability zones
Correct resource deletion order prevents errors and unexpected charges
New AWS accounts may require verification for certain services like CloudFront
Target groups connect load balancers to EC2 instances
